Gear design–as in, designing gears–is typically late college-level study. The math isn’t all that bad, but getting to the simple math means going through nasty math.

If you’re talking about designing a gear train, or a gearbox, or a belt drive (which uses similar principles), that’s a lot simpler and will have quite a few videos.

Gear Basics - FRCDesign.org

A comprehensive learning guide and technical reference for FRC design using Onshape.

Not a video per say but you can go through the learning course here and learn the fundamentals. The gear section might be a bit overwhelming if you don’t have a good foundation though.

If you mean actual gear design, theres featurescripts for that in onshape.

If you want to accurately model gears I really like the iterative hobbing-like approach described here: Hobby CAD, CNC, and resin casting

The common involute curve approach to modeling gears does a really bad job at capturing the undercut required for low tooth count gears as well as the trochoidal gear tooth root geometry that results from the hobbing process.

There’s really just two calculations you need for FRC: Ratio and tooth bending strength. For most FRC things where you aren’t going out into nuttyness you can ignore tooth bending. Knowing roughly where you are going to get into nasty wear due to excessive contact stress would be nice, but we normally solve this with “change the gears”…

It would be nice if someone ran out tooth bending strength numbers for the 7075 gears and the steel gears; maybe a chart. I don’t know if I have the bandwidth to take it on, though. The funny profile shifted gears are different from normal profile strength due to the reduced root thickness.

Weldingrod1:

Ratio and tooth bending strength.

If you care about tooth bending, you care more about tooth contact stresses which are generally higher than the bending stresses.

Weldingrod1:

It would be nice if someone ran out tooth bending strength numbers for the 7075 gears and the steel gears; maybe a chart. I don’t know if I have the bandwidth to take it on, though. The funny profile shifted gears are different from normal profile strength due to the reduced root thickness.

Agma contact and bending formulas exist and will give you the answer you are looking for.
